00:02:58,446 --> 00:03:01,432
looking at Twitter, because that's easier than researching.

58
00:03:02,338 --> 00:03:06,540
And at one point I came across this quote and I thought,

59
00:03:06,540 --> 00:03:08,160
this really encapsulates I think

60
00:03:08,160 --> 00:03:10,401
what our struggle is right now.

61
00:03:10,401 --> 00:03:14,642
And that is, we have to deliver all this information

62
00:03:14,642 --> 00:03:16,122
and we've only really got to the point

63
00:03:16,122 --> 00:03:18,343
where we can dress it up a little bit about with,

64
00:03:18,343 --> 00:03:20,523
we really need to get across,

65
00:03:20,523 --> 00:03:23,024
give me 12 ram horns for a plus three sword,

66
00:03:23,024 --> 00:03:25,265
but we can kind of gild the lily a bit

67
00:03:25,265 --> 00:03:28,486
with the gravid plane and the codicils and realm voids

68
00:03:28,486 --> 00:03:29,306
and all that stuff.

69
00:03:30,469 --> 00:03:32,010
But is it any better?

70
00:03:32,010 --> 00:03:34,792
I mean, that's the question.

71
00:03:34,792 --> 00:03:36,493
Boom, look at that.

72
00:03:36,493 --> 00:03:36,974
Pretty cool.

73
00:03:36,974 --> 00:03:45,560
This is the question I want to address in this presentation.

74
00:03:45,560 --> 00:03:48,142
We're gonna talk about why it hasn't gotten

75
00:03:48,142 --> 00:03:50,423
that much better on the whole.

76
00:03:50,423 --> 00:03:53,726
And I think to start with,

77
00:03:53,726 --> 00:03:55,847
maybe it's something to do with how we view our jobs.

78
00:03:57,739 --> 00:03:59,400
So I think we often start with this assumption

79
00:03:59,400 --> 00:04:04,723
that we, the writers, need to transmit the story

80
00:04:04,723 --> 00:04:07,124
to the player, who is essentially like a reader.

81
00:04:07,124 --> 00:04:10,666
There's a lot of information to cover,

82
00:04:10,666 --> 00:04:13,368
and we need to include backstory and plot,

83
00:04:13,368 --> 00:04:15,469
and more backstory and characters,

84
00:04:15,469 --> 00:04:17,590
oh, you should have those locations, yes.

85
00:04:17,590 --> 00:04:19,091
Critical D, why not more backstory?

86
00:04:19,091 --> 00:04:22,013
We're all building A plots, B plots, Z plots.

87
00:04:22,013 --> 00:04:27,056
A whole bunch of stuff needs to get shoved into our story.

88
00:04:29,063 --> 00:04:32,205
And the experience can be very unequal

89
00:04:32,205 --> 00:04:34,006
on either side of that arrow.

90
00:04:34,006 --> 00:04:36,188
And on our side, we're like sitting there thinking,

91
00:04:36,188 --> 00:04:38,449
we're like Mary Shelley, we've invented a new genre.

92
00:04:38,449 --> 00:04:43,051
Because we've given all this amazing lore.

93
00:04:43,051 --> 00:04:46,453
But on the other side, on the player side,

94
00:04:46,453 --> 00:04:47,394
it can be different.

95
00:04:47,394 --> 00:04:50,776
It can be kind of like, what, who?

96
00:04:50,776 --> 00:04:52,417
And we have to be careful about that.

97
00:04:52,417 --> 00:04:54,158
And there's some techniques I'm gonna cover

98
00:04:54,158 --> 00:04:56,439
to help connect people to that information

99
00:04:56,439 --> 00:04:57,340
we're trying to give them.

100
00:04:59,772 --> 00:05:03,054
we labor under maybe a fantasy

101
00:05:03,054 --> 00:05:05,035
that if you pair a well-written story

102
00:05:05,035 --> 00:05:07,176
with a reasonable player,

103
00:05:07,176 --> 00:05:09,938
you're gonna get this love affair,

104
00:05:09,938 --> 00:05:11,999
and this love affair is gonna last forever.

105
00:05:11,999 --> 00:05:14,241
Like these two crazy kids.

106
00:05:14,241 --> 00:05:16,662
I think it's gonna work.

107
00:05:16,662 --> 00:05:17,083
But all too often,

108
00:05:17,083 --> 00:05:20,985
because we're making them drink from the fire hose,

109
00:05:20,985 --> 00:05:23,006
the reaction is more like,

110
00:05:23,006 --> 00:05:24,307
yeah, okay, I don't get it, bye.

111
00:05:24,307 --> 00:05:26,889
I'm not connected to this game.

112
00:05:29,593 --> 00:05:31,574
So I see instead of an arrow,

113
00:05:31,574 --> 00:05:33,356
I see it more like a virtuous circle.

114
00:05:33,356 --> 00:05:38,800
And it starts with the things that we are going to give.

115
00:05:38,800 --> 00:05:40,281
We're going to give emotional story,

116
00:05:40,281 --> 00:05:41,943
we're gonna give character relationships,

117
00:05:41,943 --> 00:05:44,485
participatory art, compelling choices,

118
00:05:44,485 --> 00:05:47,607
and that the players are gonna come back with,

119
00:05:47,607 --> 00:05:49,589
when they experience their emotional story,

120
00:05:49,589 --> 00:05:52,731
they're gonna come back with emotional investment.

121
00:05:52,731 --> 00:05:54,352
They react to the character relationships

122
00:05:54,352 --> 00:05:57,034
with their ships and their memes and all that cool stuff.

123
00:05:57,802 --> 00:05:59,022
And the art becomes cosplay.

124
00:05:59,022 --> 00:06:02,024
And the choices become tears and loyalty,

125
00:06:02,024 --> 00:06:04,545
and I'm coming back and I'm playing season two or whatever.

126
00:06:04,545 --> 00:06:07,067
But we have to sustain this circle

127
00:06:07,067 --> 00:06:10,108
because that's how we create the connection.

128
00:06:10,108 --> 00:06:12,630
And the connection is extremely important.

129
00:06:12,630 --> 00:06:15,151
The connection is what brings people back.

130
00:06:15,151 --> 00:06:19,734
The connection is what builds loyalty or builds investment.

131
00:06:19,734 --> 00:06:21,675
And even monetization.

132
00:06:23,944 --> 00:06:28,454
And if you come away from this talk with one idea in your head, if everything I babble

133
00:06:28,454 --> 00:06:32,241
about just like goes completely in one ear and out the other.

134
00:06:33,566 --> 00:06:38,328
Remember this, connection is better than information.

135
00:06:38,328 --> 00:06:40,469
Information is just data.

136
00:06:40,469 --> 00:06:43,231
Your job as writers is to form a connection.

137
00:06:43,231 --> 00:06:44,651
You are artists.

138
00:06:44,651 --> 00:06:47,233
You are looking inside of your own heart

139
00:06:47,233 --> 00:06:50,254
so that you can connect with someone else's heart.

140
00:06:50,254 --> 00:06:52,675
Information is just, that's for robots.

141
00:06:52,675 --> 00:06:54,116
You're not robots.

142
00:06:54,116 --> 00:06:57,098
The people playing these games are not robots.

143
00:06:57,098 --> 00:06:59,599
We have to strive for something deeper than that.

144
00:07:00,431 --> 00:07:05,275
Information will take care of itself if people feel connected to what you're trying to get at.

145
00:07:05,275 --> 00:07:11,581
So this is the big takeaway. You can leave now if you want. I just gave it all away.

146
00:07:11,581 --> 00:07:18,307
I just wanted to underline this. I'm really sorry I couldn't make it blink.

147
00:07:20,682 --> 00:07:21,582
I'll do better next time.

148
00:07:21,582 --> 00:07:24,403
All right, so now that I've established

149
00:07:24,403 --> 00:07:26,503
kind of my large goals,

150
00:07:26,503 --> 00:07:28,104
let's talk about actual techniques.

151
00:07:28,104 --> 00:07:31,685
And I'm gonna drive through about six proven things

152
00:07:31,685 --> 00:07:33,725
I know can work and that you can take away

153
00:07:33,725 --> 00:07:37,566
and apply to your own games and your own narratives.

154
00:07:37,566 --> 00:07:39,246
First, there's right story for right audience,

155
00:07:39,246 --> 00:07:43,707
crafting payoffs, something I call writing for the triangle,

156
00:07:43,707 --> 00:07:46,288
compelling choices, and sharing is caring.

157
00:07:47,472 --> 00:07:49,596
And I realized that I said there were six,

158
00:07:49,596 --> 00:07:54,085
and so I'm gonna include a bonus, there will be a cat.

159
00:07:56,288 --> 00:08:01,732
This comes because when I used to give these seminars for the writers and designers at Telltale,

160
00:08:01,732 --> 00:08:07,556
the only time we could do it was at lunch, and I knew that they were sitting out there angry that I had taken away their lunch.

161
00:08:07,556 --> 00:08:16,062
So I would always promise them, hey, no matter what boring stuff is in my slideshow, I will include a picture of a cute kitty.

162
00:08:16,062 --> 00:08:23,587
And that tended to mollify them. So I continue to use that, and it might work on you, too. Hopefully.

163
00:08:23,587 --> 00:08:25,348
Oh, God, I love transitions.

164
00:08:27,007 --> 00:08:29,048
So right story for the right audience.

165
00:08:29,048 --> 00:08:31,209
This is where it often begins,

166
00:08:31,209 --> 00:08:35,170
and it can go wrong right from the start.

167
00:08:35,170 --> 00:08:37,011
You have to know who your audience is,

168
00:08:37,011 --> 00:08:39,292
and you have to know what they care about.

169
00:08:39,292 --> 00:08:41,153
I think sometimes we assume we know.

170
00:08:42,667 --> 00:08:48,172
I was in a room recently with some devs who were kind of like blue sky brainstorming

171
00:08:48,172 --> 00:08:53,336
What is our game gonna be like and they were throwing out references. They were like I love you know

172
00:08:53,336 --> 00:08:56,898
Mario Kart, and I kind of want to be like that and like

173
00:08:56,898 --> 00:09:02,343
Super Smash Bros. and playing a lot of that so they were drawing in all these like really credible references

174
00:09:03,582 --> 00:09:05,263
mainly from sort of those Nintendo products.

175
00:09:05,263 --> 00:09:10,426
And I said, well, okay, so who's our audience?

176
00:09:10,426 --> 00:09:13,207
And they said, oh, it's like women age 50 to 60.

177
00:09:13,207 --> 00:09:15,749
And I went, it's totally possible

178
00:09:15,749 --> 00:09:18,030
that these women would get those references,

179
00:09:18,030 --> 00:09:21,392
but we didn't ask anybody and they just assumed they knew.

180
00:09:21,392 --> 00:09:22,993
And I think that's where it often goes wrong

181
00:09:22,993 --> 00:09:25,334
is that it needs to start with a conversation.

182
00:09:25,334 --> 00:09:26,655
You need to go to your audience,

183
00:09:26,655 --> 00:09:28,436
first of all, identify your audience.

184
00:09:29,198 --> 00:09:32,220
Second, go to them, ask them, what are you into?

185
00:09:32,220 --> 00:09:33,060
What do you value?

186
00:09:33,060 --> 00:09:34,621
Or what are you looking for in a game?

187
00:09:34,621 --> 00:09:38,503
Because it's totally possible that you could come

188
00:09:38,503 --> 00:09:41,124
to the table with some really credible pitch

189
00:09:41,124 --> 00:09:43,066
that included a lot of high quality references,

190
00:09:43,066 --> 00:09:45,087
like, it's gonna be like True Detective,

191
00:09:45,087 --> 00:09:46,848
wrapped in the best parts of Jessica Jones,

192
00:09:46,848 --> 00:09:49,809
and in a gritty fantasy setting with real political intrigue

193
00:09:49,809 --> 00:09:51,810
and like, that sounds really cool.

194
00:09:51,810 --> 00:09:53,892
But what if your audience is like,

195
00:09:55,621 --> 00:09:57,582
They don't get those references,

196
00:09:57,582 --> 00:09:59,463
those values are not important to them.

197
00:09:59,463 --> 00:10:01,224
So you sort of wasted everybody's time

198
00:10:01,224 --> 00:10:05,866
and it's easy to get caught up in what you love,

199
00:10:05,866 --> 00:10:11,629
but remember, there's a second part of that equation.

200
00:10:11,629 --> 00:10:13,070
And what can help you with this are,

201
00:10:13,070 --> 00:10:16,351
for a long time we talked about demographics,

202
00:10:16,351 --> 00:10:17,532
and demographics

203
00:10:18,493 --> 00:10:21,437
are now seen as kind of limited, like males 18 to 35.

204
00:10:21,437 --> 00:10:23,580
Well, a male 18 to 35, an 18-year-old male

205
00:10:23,580 --> 00:10:26,164
could be just getting out of high school,

206
00:10:26,164 --> 00:10:30,070
and a 35-year-old male could be like,

207
00:10:30,070 --> 00:10:31,712
have kids and own his own house.

208
00:10:31,712 --> 00:10:33,875
And their values and what they're looking for

209
00:10:33,875 --> 00:10:34,776
are not really aligned.

210
00:10:35,803 --> 00:10:37,464
So now we talk more about segmentation,

211
00:10:37,464 --> 00:10:39,205
and there have been a couple of great talks,

212
00:10:39,205 --> 00:10:40,985
so I won't go over segmentation too much,

213
00:10:40,985 --> 00:10:44,246
but it's really more about thinking,

214
00:10:44,246 --> 00:10:45,827
slicing through that entire demographic

215
00:10:45,827 --> 00:10:48,428
and looking more for personality traits

216
00:10:48,428 --> 00:10:50,648
or like play styles or goals,

217
00:10:50,648 --> 00:10:52,529
what your audience is looking for.

218
00:10:53,860 --> 00:10:56,462
So like as an example, we did for Panda Pop recently,

219
00:10:56,462 --> 00:11:00,807
we were thinking about what if we had a more robust story

220
00:11:00,807 --> 00:11:02,669
in Panda Pop, because there kind of isn't a story,

221
00:11:02,669 --> 00:11:03,830
it's very suggested.

222
00:11:03,830 --> 00:11:06,613
So we went to the audience and we talked to a lot,

223
00:11:06,613 --> 00:11:09,496
you know, we talked to men, we talked to women, all ages,

224
00:11:09,496 --> 00:11:12,439
and we sliced sort of one demographic.

225
00:11:13,019 --> 00:11:15,862
and did a little deep dive on like, what do you like about this game?

226
00:11:15,862 --> 00:11:19,685
Like, what are you looking for when you when you get into Panda Pop?

227
00:11:19,685 --> 00:11:23,109
And there were three groups. And first of all, it was a skill group.

228
00:11:23,109 --> 00:11:26,712
And these women were really interested in they wanted high scores.

229
00:11:26,712 --> 00:11:29,755
They love to discover strategies. So like how to bank the,

230
00:11:29,755 --> 00:11:34,539
you know, like the bubble and understanding the mechanics and using all the various

231
00:11:34,539 --> 00:11:37,562
like weaponry on stuff. They were super skill based.

232
00:11:38,498 --> 00:11:39,699
And then there was a second group,

233
00:11:39,699 --> 00:11:42,761
and they were more resonating with the content.

234
00:11:42,761 --> 00:11:45,443
They liked the cute pandas, they liked the magical world.

235
00:11:45,443 --> 00:11:48,025
That's what was getting them back into the game.

236
00:11:48,025 --> 00:11:51,528
And then the third group was the escape group,

237
00:11:51,528 --> 00:11:55,530
like the, this is my stress relief, this is my me time.

238
00:11:55,530 --> 00:11:59,673
It was a little place they could go to get away from it all.

239
00:12:00,952 --> 00:12:04,895
And that was really instructive for thinking about the story

240
00:12:04,895 --> 00:12:08,397
because it automatically gives you a sense of

241
00:12:08,397 --> 00:12:10,098
who your story might appeal to.

242
00:12:10,098 --> 00:12:12,540
And or, even better, we started to think about

243
00:12:12,540 --> 00:12:15,983
how could we include some of these elements in the story

244
00:12:15,983 --> 00:12:19,245
so that players could feel they were reflected somehow.

245
00:12:19,245 --> 00:12:21,867
Like, could some of the pandas be very,

246
00:12:21,867 --> 00:12:24,029
like, skill-minded pandas who take pride

247
00:12:24,029 --> 00:12:25,130
in how well they do.

248
00:12:25,130 --> 00:12:27,531
And...

249
00:12:28,315 --> 00:12:30,516
we're not the only people who think about this.

250
00:12:30,516 --> 00:12:32,877
I mean, Netflix, oh, this is interesting.

251
00:12:32,877 --> 00:12:34,877
They talk about taste communities.

