00:14:02,796 --> 00:14:05,958
Okay, incredible story template.

288
00:14:05,958 --> 00:14:07,840
You have, you know, what does it look like?

289
00:14:07,840 --> 00:14:09,601
Well, it's got a call to action, there's an arc,

290
00:14:09,601 --> 00:14:11,242
you know, there's shenanigans in the middle

291
00:14:11,242 --> 00:14:12,964
where you have adventures and fight monsters

292
00:14:12,964 --> 00:14:16,086
and stormtroopers, and then there's a resolution

293
00:14:16,086 --> 00:14:18,808
where there's a big conflict

294
00:14:18,808 --> 00:14:22,210
and the hero learns something about herself and changes.

295
00:14:24,288 --> 00:14:26,589
And that works really well because it maps really well

296
00:14:26,589 --> 00:14:29,570
or has mapped really well to like triple A,

297
00:14:29,570 --> 00:14:31,171
single player type of games

298
00:14:31,171 --> 00:14:33,212
where you're gonna start with a tutorial.

299
00:14:33,212 --> 00:14:34,213
It's like, how do I get involved?

300
00:14:34,213 --> 00:14:35,753
And then there's gonna be a mid game

301
00:14:35,753 --> 00:14:37,915
and that's all your levels.

302
00:14:37,915 --> 00:14:39,695
And then there's the final boss who comes in

303
00:14:39,695 --> 00:14:42,937
and you fight and the game ends and boom,

304
00:14:42,937 --> 00:14:46,399
it kind of maps nicely over the top.

305
00:14:46,399 --> 00:14:48,820
But we're in a different era now.

306
00:14:48,820 --> 00:14:50,861
So free to play kind of looks more like this, doesn't it?

307
00:14:52,058 --> 00:14:53,600
You have your fatui and then there's like,

308
00:14:53,600 --> 00:14:55,844
you start churning through those levels

309
00:14:55,844 --> 00:14:57,987
and you get like level 500 and level 1000,

310
00:14:57,987 --> 00:15:01,954
but it just keeps kind of pointing out infinitely.

311
00:15:01,954 --> 00:15:04,958
So that doesn't look like the hero's journey.

312
00:15:04,958 --> 00:15:06,521
There's no arc, there's no resolution.

313
00:15:07,359 --> 00:15:13,821
So then what? What kind of story is this? I say consider the humble sitcom structure.

314
00:15:13,821 --> 00:15:20,042
I mean sitcoms are built like this. They start with a cast of characters and they don't know

315
00:15:20,042 --> 00:15:24,803
how many seasons they're going to go. So they really have to build the story to be

316
00:15:24,803 --> 00:15:31,624
somewhat pliably infinite. And their structure looks more like this. We have all these ups and

317
00:15:31,624 --> 00:15:35,105
downs. And they're way more frequent, which

318
00:15:36,162 --> 00:15:38,907
we know suits a mobile environment a lot better.

319
00:15:40,509 --> 00:15:41,389
So I'm not saying you have to.

320
00:15:41,389 --> 00:15:42,290
I'm saying consider.

321
00:15:42,290 --> 00:15:44,330
This is a really interesting possibility.

322
00:15:44,330 --> 00:15:46,311
And I'll make one more play for it.

323
00:15:46,311 --> 00:15:47,971
I'm not being paid by the sitcom industry

324
00:15:47,971 --> 00:15:48,831
or anything like that.

325
00:15:48,831 --> 00:15:51,012
I just really see that there's potential here.

326
00:15:51,012 --> 00:15:54,353
First of all, sitcoms are based on characters

327
00:15:54,353 --> 00:15:55,973
with unresolvable dilemmas.

328
00:15:55,973 --> 00:15:59,034
Like Leslie Knope is always going to be naively optimistic.

329
00:15:59,034 --> 00:15:59,874
She's not gonna change.

330
00:15:59,874 --> 00:16:02,535
Joey's never gonna turn into a rocket scientist.

331
00:16:02,535 --> 00:16:06,016
Ron Swanson is never gonna believe in government.

332
00:16:07,757 --> 00:16:10,859
But that's fine. That's what we want out of that entertainment.

333
00:16:10,859 --> 00:16:16,923
And putting those characters in conflict is how you generate stories over and over and over.

334
00:16:16,923 --> 00:16:18,704
And it can scale infinitely.

335
00:16:18,704 --> 00:16:20,386
They also have clear act breaks.

336
00:16:20,386 --> 00:16:24,649
So every sitcom, if it's a half an hour, it's got three act breaks.

337
00:16:24,649 --> 00:16:28,031
And that also gives you a really nice rhythm.

338
00:16:28,031 --> 00:16:30,393
And it's something that you can map onto your own stories.

339
00:16:31,924 --> 00:16:33,666
They're smaller, producible arcs.

340
00:16:33,666 --> 00:16:34,787
It's not like a gigantic 60-hour mega arc.

341
00:16:34,787 --> 00:16:39,311
You can do smaller iterations on that.

342
00:16:39,311 --> 00:16:43,095
And the scenes tend to be character-based.

343
00:16:43,095 --> 00:16:45,738
I mean, you could do most sitcom scenes in a room,

344
00:16:45,738 --> 00:16:48,440
an empty room with two chairs and two characters.

345
00:16:48,440 --> 00:16:49,902
That could be a sitcom scene.

346
00:16:49,902 --> 00:16:50,763
It's totally doable.

347
00:16:50,763 --> 00:16:53,665
And that's way closer to

348
00:16:55,247 --> 00:16:56,830
how we need to produce things in mobile.

349
00:16:56,830 --> 00:16:58,853
It has to be somewhat cheap,

350
00:16:58,853 --> 00:17:00,876
somewhat easy to produce, and quick.

351
00:17:00,876 --> 00:17:02,819
We have a lot of content to put out.

352
00:17:02,819 --> 00:17:04,461
And so if you look at sitcoms,

353
00:17:04,461 --> 00:17:06,324
there's a nice parallel there.

354
00:17:06,324 --> 00:17:08,728
But don't forget.

355
00:17:09,753 --> 00:17:11,354
do fit your content to its format,

356
00:17:11,354 --> 00:17:13,976
especially if you're working with a big IP.

357
00:17:13,976 --> 00:17:16,258
So for example, what I mean is,

358
00:17:16,258 --> 00:17:18,779
in Harry Potter we have like the books

359
00:17:18,779 --> 00:17:22,061
have these amazing set piece adventure things,

360
00:17:22,061 --> 00:17:24,923
you know, the lake of fire with a million zombies

361
00:17:24,923 --> 00:17:26,864
coming out and attacking them.

362
00:17:26,864 --> 00:17:27,705
The movies do this too,

363
00:17:27,705 --> 00:17:29,326
because they're visual medium

364
00:17:29,326 --> 00:17:30,726
and movies have to be a spectacle.

365
00:17:32,134 --> 00:17:35,095
However, with Hogwarts Mystery,

366
00:17:35,095 --> 00:17:40,517
we knew we needed to be somewhat more contained and smaller,

367
00:17:40,517 --> 00:17:43,458
but still feel very meaningful and connected.

368
00:17:43,458 --> 00:17:46,359
So Hogwarts Mystery is all about characters.

369
00:17:46,359 --> 00:17:48,440
There's a million characters and you meet them all

370
00:17:48,440 --> 00:17:49,740
and they have different personalities

371
00:17:49,740 --> 00:17:52,401
and putting those personalities into a room together

372
00:17:52,401 --> 00:17:54,662
is how we drive the drama.

373
00:17:54,662 --> 00:17:57,202
We don't do it with giant set pieces,

374
00:17:57,202 --> 00:17:59,223
we do it with character drama.

375
00:17:59,223 --> 00:18:02,024
And that's because we're fitting the content to the format.

376
00:18:04,737 --> 00:18:07,319
All right, number two, crafting payoffs.

377
00:18:07,319 --> 00:18:10,422
Okay, so now that you've got your audience in the door

378
00:18:10,422 --> 00:18:12,784
and you're telling them the right story,

379
00:18:12,784 --> 00:18:15,246
how do you keep them there?

380
00:18:15,246 --> 00:18:17,588
Regular narrative payoffs bond a player to a game.

381
00:18:17,588 --> 00:18:19,550
What you wanna do is establish a habit

382
00:18:19,550 --> 00:18:23,753
or establish an expectation of this payoff

383
00:18:23,753 --> 00:18:24,414
that's gonna come.

384
00:18:26,208 --> 00:18:30,511
And you need to do that by starting with emotional storytelling, not informational storytelling.

385
00:18:30,511 --> 00:18:35,315
You will never hook anybody with a bunch of data about, here's some plot points and a

386
00:18:35,315 --> 00:18:38,157
list of planets you're going to visit.

387
00:18:38,157 --> 00:18:38,698
Nobody cares.

388
00:18:38,698 --> 00:18:40,939
They just don't.

389
00:18:40,939 --> 00:18:43,401
Remember what I said, connection is better than information.

390
00:18:43,401 --> 00:18:45,143
Start with a connection.

391
00:18:45,143 --> 00:18:50,907
And that means starting with a theme, because themes are what people feel.

392
00:18:50,907 --> 00:18:53,849
Theme is a really easy way to explain to people how they're supposed to feel about your game

393
00:18:53,849 --> 00:18:54,530
or feel in your game.

394
00:18:55,439 --> 00:18:57,240
And you have to know what it is.

395
00:18:57,240 --> 00:18:59,182
I can't tell you how many devs I've talked to

396
00:18:59,182 --> 00:19:00,223
that they would explain their story.

397
00:19:00,223 --> 00:19:01,384
You go here, you go there.

398
00:19:01,384 --> 00:19:03,145
And I'm like, okay, that sounds cool,

399
00:19:03,145 --> 00:19:04,206
but what's your theme?

400
00:19:04,206 --> 00:19:06,568
What's the theme of the game?

401
00:19:06,568 --> 00:19:09,350
And just, look, I just haven't thought about it.

402
00:19:09,350 --> 00:19:10,832
So think about it.

403
00:19:10,832 --> 00:19:12,713
Examples of themes are like.

404
00:19:13,988 --> 00:19:15,409
When we were doing Game of Thrones,

405
00:19:15,409 --> 00:19:18,872
we talked with some people who knew George R.R. Martin,

406
00:19:18,872 --> 00:19:20,853
and we talked a lot about this idea

407
00:19:20,853 --> 00:19:22,534
of your passions will destroy you.

408
00:19:22,534 --> 00:19:24,635
And that's a theme that runs all the way

409
00:19:24,635 --> 00:19:25,576
through Game of Thrones.

410
00:19:25,576 --> 00:19:28,938
And we see characters who, like Robb Stark, spoilers,

411
00:19:28,938 --> 00:19:33,821
his passion for his father, that loyalty,

412
00:19:33,821 --> 00:19:37,324
drives him to pursue revenge, which leads to his death

413
00:19:37,324 --> 00:19:39,145
and the death of a lot of people he loves.

414
00:19:39,145 --> 00:19:41,567
And that kind of thing you see all over the place.

415
00:19:42,807 --> 00:19:47,529
And in mobile, it kind of, I was trying to think of examples of this in mobile, and I

