00:24:03,606 --> 00:24:06,008
They were always something we would evaluate and say,

505
00:24:06,008 --> 00:24:07,909
do we have our big payoff for Potter?

506
00:24:07,909 --> 00:24:10,890
It's like, do we have the scene pivot and do we have

507
00:24:10,890 --> 00:24:14,672
something to send players off to the next location?

508
00:24:14,672 --> 00:24:16,913
So making it more of a formal.

509
00:24:17,253 --> 00:24:25,799
Structure is really important to make sure you're not missing that and that you're creating that habit

510
00:24:25,799 --> 00:24:29,962
And remember that this is a retention tool like once you form a habit

511
00:24:29,962 --> 00:24:34,805
Don't don't let it go like that's really tough. So be consistent and

512
00:24:34,805 --> 00:24:42,351
Deliver on the promise of your theme. It's important to deliver on that promise and speaking of promise. Hey, what about that cat?

513
00:24:42,351 --> 00:24:45,913
You told us there was a cat and frankly, I don't think you deserve the cat yet

514
00:24:46,509 --> 00:24:48,870
That's just me, that's how I'm feeling.

515
00:24:48,870 --> 00:24:50,031
You can't force me.

516
00:24:50,031 --> 00:24:54,633
All right, so now that we've got our audience,

517
00:24:54,633 --> 00:24:57,615
we've got some sort of cadence,

518
00:24:57,615 --> 00:25:00,516
now let's talk about this notion of writing for the triangle.

519
00:25:00,516 --> 00:25:02,657
And this is a really easy technique to take

520
00:25:02,657 --> 00:25:04,638
and use yourself, or at least be aware of

521
00:25:04,638 --> 00:25:06,599
when you're doing it.

522
00:25:06,599 --> 00:25:07,740
A lot of times we have...

523
00:25:09,152 --> 00:25:10,773
dialogue between two NPCs.

524
00:25:10,773 --> 00:25:11,994
And they can be really cool NPCs.

525
00:25:11,994 --> 00:25:13,855
They can be very well-written, of course they are,

526
00:25:13,855 --> 00:25:17,597
because you guys are great writers.

527
00:25:17,597 --> 00:25:20,299
And you got Cersei, and she's very interesting and evil,

528
00:25:20,299 --> 00:25:21,900
and she's gonna say something cool.

529
00:25:21,900 --> 00:25:23,501
And Tyrion is super funny and witty,

530
00:25:23,501 --> 00:25:25,021
and he's gonna say something cool.

531
00:25:25,021 --> 00:25:26,943
So we spend all our dramatic energy

532
00:25:26,943 --> 00:25:30,184
in that conversation between these two characters,

533
00:25:30,184 --> 00:25:33,647
because we know it's gonna be fun and fireworks.

534
00:25:34,843 --> 00:25:38,186
What we forget about, though, is the player.

535
00:25:38,186 --> 00:25:41,388
The player's sitting there and it's now non-interactive.

536
00:25:41,388 --> 00:25:44,330
I mean, and that's fine for TV, that's fine for movies,

537
00:25:44,330 --> 00:25:45,671
that's what we expect.

538
00:25:45,671 --> 00:25:47,472
But if they're sitting there with a phone in their hand,

539
00:25:47,472 --> 00:25:51,074
they do want a little bit of that interactivity.

540
00:25:51,074 --> 00:25:52,895
So are we forming a connection?

541
00:25:52,895 --> 00:25:56,938
No, this is information, this is one way.

542
00:25:56,938 --> 00:26:00,040
So even the best dialogue then becomes,

543
00:26:00,040 --> 00:26:03,102
kind of lands in that information bucket.

544
00:26:03,102 --> 00:26:04,163
So how do you fix this?

545
00:26:05,873 --> 00:26:07,495
This is a really common way to do it,

546
00:26:07,495 --> 00:26:08,496
and we did it in Harry Potter.

547
00:26:08,496 --> 00:26:10,457
This is an example of how it works.

548
00:26:10,457 --> 00:26:13,520
This is Penny, and Penny's currently engaged

549
00:26:13,520 --> 00:26:17,423
in a project to create decorations.

550
00:26:17,423 --> 00:26:18,904
And her teacher, Professor Flitwick,

551
00:26:18,904 --> 00:26:21,326
has told her you are not to use magic

552
00:26:21,326 --> 00:26:24,148
to create these decorations, and she follows rules.

553
00:26:24,148 --> 00:26:28,311
So she is of the opinion we shouldn't use magic

554
00:26:28,311 --> 00:26:29,132
to enhance the decorations.

555
00:26:29,132 --> 00:26:31,514
So character one states an opinion.

556
00:26:32,806 --> 00:26:33,846
Then you have character two,

557
00:26:33,846 --> 00:26:37,507
and character two usually has the opposite opinion,

558
00:26:37,507 --> 00:26:40,047
or at least a different opinion.

559
00:26:40,047 --> 00:26:42,448
This is all well and good.

560
00:26:42,448 --> 00:26:46,749
Then the two characters turn to the main character,

561
00:26:46,749 --> 00:26:48,769
the player, and ask an opinion.

562
00:26:48,769 --> 00:26:52,730
They solicit participation, they solicit the opinion.

563
00:26:52,730 --> 00:26:55,371
And I want you to note the positions of these characters

564
00:26:55,371 --> 00:26:58,531
because that's what I'm talking about.

565
00:26:58,531 --> 00:27:00,892
We're starting to form that triangle physically.

566
00:27:00,892 --> 00:27:01,892
You're telling the player.

567
00:27:02,962 --> 00:27:05,064
that they are part of what's going on.

568
00:27:05,064 --> 00:27:07,566
And the camera work here reinforces that.

569
00:27:07,566 --> 00:27:13,571
And then we allow for actual input.

570
00:27:13,571 --> 00:27:15,974
So here's the interface and the choice then becomes

571
00:27:15,974 --> 00:27:19,077
let's use magic or don't use magic.

572
00:27:19,077 --> 00:27:21,539
And here's the most important thing

573
00:27:21,539 --> 00:27:23,641
that I think people forget about a lot.

574
00:27:26,912 --> 00:27:33,923
feedback. So the narrative solicits your input and then gives you feedback to say,

575
00:27:33,923 --> 00:27:36,987
I heard what you said. I saw what you valued.

576
00:27:38,105 --> 00:27:40,785
Your opinion matters, and now the narrative

577
00:27:40,785 --> 00:27:42,565
has changed somewhat because of that.

578
00:27:42,565 --> 00:27:43,846
We're acknowledging it.

579
00:27:43,846 --> 00:27:46,446
And in this sense, it was done nicely

580
00:27:46,446 --> 00:27:48,006
through the narrative itself.

581
00:27:48,006 --> 00:27:52,267
There wasn't an on-screen UI or anything like that.

582
00:27:52,267 --> 00:27:55,908
This is actually one of the characters saying,

583
00:27:55,908 --> 00:27:57,788
oh yeah, because Hermione told us not to.

584
00:27:57,788 --> 00:28:02,369
So what we're really doing there

585
00:28:02,369 --> 00:28:04,109
is we're taking some of that dramatic energy

586
00:28:04,109 --> 00:28:07,050
that we usually invest in an NPC dialogue.

587
00:28:08,010 --> 00:28:10,492
and using some of that energy to solicit player input.

588
00:28:10,492 --> 00:28:13,714
And then we're using some more of that energy

589
00:28:13,714 --> 00:28:16,055
to create narrative feedback.

590
00:28:16,055 --> 00:28:18,337
So you can call that branching or whatever,

591
00:28:18,337 --> 00:28:21,219
but you're forming that triangle with the player.

592
00:28:21,219 --> 00:28:26,082
They are involved in this conversation.

593
00:28:26,082 --> 00:28:28,623
And so that's where the triangle comes from.

594
00:28:28,623 --> 00:28:30,445
And that's where you get that connection

595
00:28:30,445 --> 00:28:32,846
because now they're invested in this conversation.

596
00:28:32,846 --> 00:28:34,107
They had some input.

597
00:28:34,107 --> 00:28:36,628
They're interested to see what happens next.

598
00:28:41,618 --> 00:28:44,880
So now that we've got them talking to the game,

599
00:28:44,880 --> 00:28:47,161
how do we create those choices that are compelling?

600
00:28:47,161 --> 00:28:48,762
Because not all choices are created equal.

601
00:28:48,762 --> 00:28:55,927
I'll tell you this, good choices are a sleight of hand.

602
00:28:55,927 --> 00:28:57,908
What you're really doing as devs, as creators,

603
00:28:57,908 --> 00:29:01,911
is you're implanting ideas in the player's head.

604
00:29:01,911 --> 00:29:07,274
And then at a key moment, you ask them for their opinion,

605
00:29:07,274 --> 00:29:08,054
and you put those

606
00:29:09,497 --> 00:29:15,741
those topics on screen as if the player thought of them themselves. What? That's the best form of

607
00:29:15,741 --> 00:29:23,126
a choice because it feels like the player is like, oh yeah, this is what I was thinking of anyway.

608
00:29:23,126 --> 00:29:27,689
And they should feel like they are organically arise from the player's own mind.

609
00:29:28,822 --> 00:29:31,686
And you can contrast this with choices that arise externally,

610
00:29:31,686 --> 00:29:32,908
like from an author.

611
00:29:32,908 --> 00:29:34,070
So for instance, if I said,

612
00:29:34,070 --> 00:29:37,736
guys, what's your favorite flavor of ice cream?

613
00:29:37,736 --> 00:29:40,301
And then I listed your options and I said,

614
00:29:40,301 --> 00:29:42,925
pistachio, chunky monkey, and banana.

615
00:29:43,526 --> 00:29:48,632
Like those are technically ice creams, but it's probably not what you were thinking.

616
00:29:48,632 --> 00:29:52,196
It's probably not even close to the range of stuff you were thinking about.

617
00:29:52,196 --> 00:29:56,742
And that can feel very much like an authored choice or an inorganic choice.

618
00:29:56,742 --> 00:29:59,565
And what I should have said was probably something like chocolate, strawberry and vanilla,

619
00:29:59,565 --> 00:30:02,809
like fairly safe, like probably something that was in your head.

620
00:30:04,974 --> 00:30:07,419
So setting that context and setting the parameters

621
00:30:07,419 --> 00:30:09,663
for what that choice could look like is really important too

622
00:30:09,663 --> 00:30:12,768
because that's how you narrow the field to something

623
00:30:12,768 --> 00:30:15,693
that you can control and use that sleight of hand magic

624
00:30:15,693 --> 00:30:17,436
to make it all seem very seamless.

625
00:30:18,772 --> 00:30:21,413
And the last thing to do is to strive to find room

626
00:30:21,413 --> 00:30:23,073
for personal expression in the choices.

627
00:30:23,073 --> 00:30:25,535
So remember, you're not conducting a survey.

628
00:30:25,535 --> 00:30:26,795
You're really trying to elicit

629
00:30:26,795 --> 00:30:28,736
some kind of personal expression,

630
00:30:28,736 --> 00:30:30,557
some sort of emotion from the player,

631
00:30:30,557 --> 00:30:32,778
because again, that's where your connection

632
00:30:32,778 --> 00:30:34,178
is gonna come from.

633
00:30:34,178 --> 00:30:36,179
If the answer's coming from their heart,

634
00:30:36,179 --> 00:30:38,180
you're probably in a really good place.

635
00:30:38,180 --> 00:30:39,701
You've really connected with them.

636
00:30:39,701 --> 00:30:44,223
And by the way, so monetization and premium choices

637
00:30:44,223 --> 00:30:47,204
fuck all this shit up, so I will get to that later.

638
00:30:48,427 --> 00:30:50,589
Let's just put that to one side for now.

639
00:30:50,589 --> 00:30:54,652
Anyway, I want to illustrate kind of what I'm talking about.

640
00:30:54,652 --> 00:30:57,193
It's fairly subtle, and so we'll do a fake case study.

641
00:30:57,193 --> 00:31:00,015
This does not exist anywhere, but I made it up for this,

642
00:31:00,015 --> 00:31:03,958
and it's called the Draco Malfoy Beatdown.

643
00:31:03,958 --> 00:31:06,560
So let's say we're in a Harry Potter game,

644
00:31:06,560 --> 00:31:09,882
and we get a prompt from the game as players,

645
00:31:09,882 --> 00:31:13,825
and it says, Draco Malfoy is coming down the hallway.

646
00:31:13,825 --> 00:31:15,006
What do you do?

647
00:31:15,006 --> 00:31:15,606
There he is.

648
00:31:16,457 --> 00:31:19,460
And your choices are duck into a broom closet,

649
00:31:19,460 --> 00:31:22,344
take out your wand and attack, and make friends.

650
00:31:22,344 --> 00:31:28,131
Now, these are all choices that don't break reality.

651
00:31:28,131 --> 00:31:29,713
But do they feel organic?

652
00:31:31,219 --> 00:31:35,062
I say no. I think there is a lot wrong with this range of choices.

653
00:31:35,062 --> 00:31:38,804
First of all, like the detail of the broom closet came completely from me, the author.

654
00:31:38,804 --> 00:31:44,428
Like I didn't say anything about the broom closet when I said Draco Malfoy is coming down the hallway.

655
00:31:44,428 --> 00:31:50,472
So in order to introducing that into the choice space is bizarre, like not what you were thinking, right?

656
00:31:52,121 --> 00:31:54,383
Taking out your wand and attacking, I guess so,

657
00:31:54,383 --> 00:31:56,805
but is he doing anything aggressive?

658
00:31:56,805 --> 00:31:59,567
Why would a player be reacting that way?

659
00:31:59,567 --> 00:32:00,488
They wouldn't.

660
00:32:00,488 --> 00:32:02,630
It's totally a suggestion from me, the author.

661
00:32:04,122 --> 00:32:06,163
And also the parameters are completely wide open.

662
00:32:06,163 --> 00:32:08,565
The question is, what would you do?

663
00:32:08,565 --> 00:32:09,926
Or what do you do?

664
00:32:09,926 --> 00:32:11,767
I mean, there's a million things I could do.

665
00:32:11,767 --> 00:32:14,449
I could run away, I could like run up and kiss him.

666
00:32:14,449 --> 00:32:16,350
Like, why aren't those represented here?

667
00:32:16,350 --> 00:32:19,171
So the choice piece is really, really problematic.

668
00:32:19,171 --> 00:32:21,693
And finally, there's no personal expression.

669
00:32:21,693 --> 00:32:23,654
Why would I be expressing any of these?

670
00:32:23,654 --> 00:32:26,156
And what does it have to do with how I'm feeling?

671
00:32:26,156 --> 00:32:27,657
There's no prompts for how to feel

672
00:32:27,657 --> 00:32:30,238
about Draco Malfoy coming down the hallway.

673
00:32:30,238 --> 00:32:31,799
It's too neutral, it's too wide open.

674
00:32:32,620 --> 00:32:36,561
So this choice is super problematic in a lot of ways, but we can fix it.

675
00:32:36,561 --> 00:32:42,023
First of all, let's give a little more context and a smaller

676
00:32:42,023 --> 00:32:44,384
parameter to the prompt.

677
00:32:44,384 --> 00:32:47,746
So here he is, he's looking a little more aggressive.

678
00:32:47,746 --> 00:32:53,368
Let's change it to Draco Malfoy challenges you to a duel in the hallway, but you

679
00:32:53,368 --> 00:32:56,349
know, dueling is against the rules.

680
00:32:56,349 --> 00:32:58,050
What do you do?

681
00:32:58,050 --> 00:33:00,051
Accept the duel, refuse the duel.

682
00:33:01,335 --> 00:33:04,016
or tell them I'll meet you later at the bike racks.

683
00:33:04,016 --> 00:33:06,658
We'll go out behind Hagrid's Hut and, you know,

684
00:33:06,658 --> 00:33:10,700
off school grounds and I'll kick your ass there.

685
00:33:10,700 --> 00:33:11,760
So we're closer.

686
00:33:11,760 --> 00:33:13,301
This is more organic.

687
00:33:13,301 --> 00:33:15,663
It's probably, when I said challenges you to a duel,

688
00:33:15,663 --> 00:33:17,724
you were probably thinking something like,

689
00:33:17,724 --> 00:33:20,605
oh, we're gonna fight, or I'm not gonna fight.

690
00:33:20,605 --> 00:33:23,747
So that binary is more organic.

691
00:33:23,747 --> 00:33:26,008
But it is also very philosophical

692
00:33:26,008 --> 00:33:27,449
because the whole thing of,

693
00:33:27,957 --> 00:33:29,039
you know, it's against the rules.

694
00:33:29,039 --> 00:33:30,761
Well, rules didn't come from you.

695
00:33:30,761 --> 00:33:32,703
Rules aren't inside of your heart.

696
00:33:32,703 --> 00:33:35,807
Rules are something that are, again, external.

697
00:33:35,807 --> 00:33:38,351
And there might be moments when following the rules

698
00:33:38,351 --> 00:33:40,694
is something emotionally engaging, but not here.

699
00:33:43,203 --> 00:33:46,185
The parameters are closed, so we really narrowed the field

700
00:33:46,185 --> 00:33:47,666
by saying you challenge to a dual.

701
00:33:47,666 --> 00:33:50,527
So the choices do feel a little more natural.

702
00:33:50,527 --> 00:33:52,469
The deferment choice is not great.

703
00:33:52,469 --> 00:33:54,450
Really, the meet later at the bike racks

704
00:33:54,450 --> 00:33:56,111
is just a way of saying,

705
00:33:56,111 --> 00:33:59,513
let's return to this exact same choice later.

706
00:33:59,513 --> 00:34:00,934
And that doesn't really do anything

707
00:34:00,934 --> 00:34:02,135
for your story or for the player.

708
00:34:02,135 --> 00:34:05,156
So the final suggestion would be,

709
00:34:05,156 --> 00:34:07,238
how could we make this a more personal,

710
00:34:07,238 --> 00:34:09,179
player-centric question?

711
00:34:10,445 --> 00:34:12,266
And here's my attempt to do that.

712
00:34:12,266 --> 00:34:13,426
So now we can change this to,

713
00:34:13,426 --> 00:34:18,228
Malfoy challenges you to a duel in front of your new crush,

714
00:34:18,228 --> 00:34:22,110
who then offers to defend you.

715
00:34:22,110 --> 00:34:25,231
And your choices are, fight Malfoy yourself, I got this.

716
00:34:25,231 --> 00:34:31,394
Leave without fighting, way of the peaceful warrior.

717
00:34:31,394 --> 00:34:32,554
Let your crush defend you.

718
00:34:34,023 --> 00:34:35,684
And then it does sort of suggest a fourth one,

719
00:34:35,684 --> 00:34:37,005
which is beat his ass together.

720
00:34:37,005 --> 00:34:41,168
So like, this is how couples bond sometimes.

721
00:34:41,168 --> 00:34:46,432
So what I did was to create a more personal version

722
00:34:46,432 --> 00:34:47,352
of the same question.

723
00:34:47,352 --> 00:34:50,014
So now instead of asking about rules,

724
00:34:50,014 --> 00:34:51,195
we put a little romance in there.

725
00:34:51,195 --> 00:34:53,417
So this is probably something more close

726
00:34:53,417 --> 00:34:56,579
to how you think and feel and your worries and anxieties,

727
00:34:56,579 --> 00:34:58,921
because that all comes out when we introduce romance

728
00:34:58,921 --> 00:35:00,201
or someone you want to impress.

729
00:35:02,342 --> 00:35:04,203
So the parameters in the context are more clear.

730
00:35:04,203 --> 00:35:05,003
What's going on?

731
00:35:05,003 --> 00:35:06,084
Who's there?

732
00:35:06,084 --> 00:35:07,344
What's your relationship to them?

733
00:35:07,344 --> 00:35:09,425
It's your crush.

734
00:35:09,425 --> 00:35:10,445
It's Draco Malfoy.

735
00:35:10,445 --> 00:35:11,205
He's being a dick.

736
00:35:11,205 --> 00:35:16,247
So, and finally, the personalization is stronger

737
00:35:16,247 --> 00:35:19,248
because now at least there's an implied relationship outcome.

738
00:35:19,248 --> 00:35:21,489
Like if your crush says, I'll defend you,

739
00:35:21,489 --> 00:35:23,249
and you say, don't.

740
00:35:24,030 --> 00:35:29,372
There's maybe some implied relationship change there, or you let them do it. Again,

741
00:35:29,372 --> 00:35:33,553
implied relationship change. And this is how to get closer to maybe what the player

742
00:35:33,553 --> 00:35:38,215
really feels and thinks inside. And when they give the game that kind of input,

743
00:35:38,215 --> 00:35:42,837
they're sharing personal information. And that's how you create a connection and a bond.

744
00:35:45,445 --> 00:35:48,348
So again, so monetization, just so you know,

745
00:35:48,348 --> 00:35:51,030
we do survive on monetization and I'm not like down on it,

746
00:35:51,030 --> 00:35:53,552
but I think it's worth calling out

747
00:35:53,552 --> 00:35:56,134
that it activates a different part of the brain.

748
00:35:56,134 --> 00:36:00,637
And it's like an acquisitive part of the brain.

749
00:36:00,637 --> 00:36:02,278
It's the brain, it's part of the brain

750
00:36:02,278 --> 00:36:03,239
that like wants something.

751
00:36:04,034 --> 00:36:08,235
And you can see it's often kind of staged that way.

752
00:36:08,235 --> 00:36:11,176
So here's an example from choices.

753
00:36:11,176 --> 00:36:11,856
And I like choices.

754
00:36:11,856 --> 00:36:13,316
I mean, I'm not down on choices or anything.

755
00:36:13,316 --> 00:36:16,517
But this is a good example of how they have to bend over

